&lt;h2 id="the-short-story-behind-my-website">The short story behind my website&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>As far as I remembered, I have built 5 different versions of my personal
website. I decided to get a website when I was doing my PhD, back in 2014 (not a
100% about sure about the timeline), in order to share some of my work. With my
(very) modest skills I built a first website using CSS, HTML and a bit of PHP,
no framework of any sort, no static site generators either. It was hosted by
1and1 (which is now &lt;a href="https://www.ionos.com/">Ionos&lt;/a>, apparently) and I used to
send updates to the server with &lt;a href="https://filezilla-project.org/">FileZilla&lt;/a>. It
was a funny looking website&amp;hellip; looked like a website from the 90&amp;rsquo;s! Shame I
didn&amp;rsquo;t take a screenshot! It lasted a year or so before I worked on a
second version.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Deploy a pkgdown website on gh-pages manually</title><link>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2020/04/2020-04-12_deploy_a_pkgdown/</link><pubDate>Sun, 12 Apr 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://kevcaz.github.io/notes/2020/04/2020-04-12_deploy_a_pkgdown/</guid><description>&lt;p>This is another note about deploying a
&lt;a href="https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=pkgdown">&lt;code>pkgdown&lt;/code>&lt;/a>&lt;sup id="fnref:1">&lt;a href="#fn:1" class="footnote-ref" role="doc-noteref">1&lt;/a>&lt;/sup> website with
&lt;a href="https://travis-ci.org/">Travis&lt;/a> on gh-pages. I had
&lt;a href="notes/ci/deploypkgdown">previously&lt;/a> used the package
&lt;a href="https://CRAN.R-project.org/package=travis">&lt;code>travis&lt;/code>&lt;/a> but I was recently
